<H5>  Summary </H5>
  Summarized Recommendation--see also Chapter 5: 
  Enterprises should not receive direct financial support for 
development of energy technology or investments in new energy 
technology. The subsidies which are granted in this direction 
should thus be abolished. On the other hand, society should 
stimulate continued basic R&amp;D cooperations and rapid 
spreading 
of R&amp;D results among enterprises. This can best be done 
through 
a certain increase in government support for jointly owned 
R&amp;D 
projects and development companies. 
  Society's most important task, however, is to create a 
climate for industrial activity which creates development power. 
The individually most important application area for improving 
the climate within the energy field is a more consistent, 
durable and in the long term credible fiscal and fee policy. 
Beyond this, it is essential, in order to improve the companies' 
supply of know-how, significantly to reinforce academic research 
within a few selective areas of technology, as well as in 
general to increase the opportunities of research to participate 
in international cooperation. 
<H3>  The Characteristics of Commercial Development of Energy 
Technology--see also Chapter 2: </H3>
  1. New technology affects society through its application. 
Ever so good technology which is not being used is therefore of 
limited value. 
  2. The company's incentive to carry out technical 
development 
is financial profitability. Since various R&amp;D projects fail, 
successful R&amp;D projects are characterized by very high 
profitability. 
  3. The time from project start to commercial introduction of 
new technology often turns out to be 10 years or more, after 
which it often takes another 10 years for projects to start 
paying off. Successful development projects therefore require 
patient financial involvement by the parties involved. 
  4. Successful product development projects are marked by the 
fact that early assessments and high-quality evaluations lead to 
a clear and early picture of the market and the properties of 
the product, which leads to the development of an effective 
product and market successes. Failed development projects are 
often due to the first assessments having been unclear. 
  5. New energy technology is mainly introduced in connection 
with new investments. Technology, particularly that which does 
not fit into existing systems, therefore achieves more rapid 
distribution during strong market growth, during structural 
changes or in industries where for other reasons there is a 
great deal of new investment. 
  6. On the customer side there is sound caution toward 
untested solutions. For large systems a commercially purchased 
reference facility of reasonable size is therefore crucial for 
further commercialization. 
  7. Well developed cooperation with the customer means that 
the necessary market orientation of the development work is 
facilitated and thus that the preconditions for success 
increase. This applies to both the development and the 
distribution phase. For development of large systems, 
cooperation with the customer is a prerequisite for success. 
  8. Energy technology is marked by high investment costs, 
long 
lifetime and high demands for accessibility of the systems. This 
leads to a certain inertia toward radical changes, and these 
take longer than in many other fields. 
<H3>  The Swedish Development of Energy Technology--see also 
Chapter 3: </H3>
  9. The Swedish energy technology development has largely 
been 
concentrated to a "technology triangle" consisting of the 
electricity-intensive basic industry, the power industry and the 
electrical engineering industry. A strong power industry and 
electrical engineering industry grew up in order to supply the 
growing basic industry, among others. A strong development need 
gradually emerged for being able to utilize the unique 
opportunities found in hydroelectric power, which was located at 
places other than the utilization centers. This led to expansion 
opportunities for the electrical engineering industry. It has 
been possible to apply the basic expertise that was created to 
other areas of technology, such as the field of nuclear 
technology. 
  10. The development usually took place in the form of 
development blocks, in which technology developers and 
technology buyers cooperated under business-like forms and with 
a distinct internal allocation of roles. 
  11. The Swedish development of energy technology appears 
unique from an international perspective. The development was 
facilitated by rapid market growth which made it easier to 
spread the technology, by successful sharing of risk between 
various players, by a stable surrounding world and, particularly 
during the post-war era, by a favorable financial situation. 
  12. Today, the development of energy technology in many ways 
faces a more difficult situation. The greater pace of changes in 
the rest of the world has led to higher concentration on short- 
term issues, the growth in energy use has decreased and the 
capital costs have increased. On the other hand, the more 
intense competition leads to more pressure on the companies to 
use their resources in the most efficient way, and the 
internationalized financial market makes financing of large 
projects easier, factors which stimulate technical development. 
  13. Within the power sector there is no longer any specific 
Swedish development of energy technology. As a result of growing 
development costs and reduced Swedish investment volume, the 
development costs must be spread over a larger market volume 
than the Swedish one. 
  14. Within the heating sector, a Swedish development course 
has a somewhat greater importance as a result of a larger 
domestic market, special needs by the customers and often lower 
development costs. In this field as well there is a growing 
internationalization, and here as well it is becoming less 
important to talk about a Swedish development course. 
  15. The deregulation and internationalization of the energy 
markets is putting the energy companies on a more equal footing 
with other industrial activity. This could possibly, primarily 
during the adjustment phase, lead to a certain reduced interest 
in sharing development risks. Just as for other capital- 
intensive processing industries, however, competitive advantages 
are to a major degree created by forward-looking investments in 
new technology, which is why the principal orientation will 
remain. 
<H3>  Society's Influence on Commercial Development of Energy 
Technology--see also Chapter 4: </H3>
  16. Society influences the technical development indirectly 
by changing the market conditions for technical development, 
here called climate factors, and by direct means of control 
aimed at the technology development or technology application, 
here called innovation support. In all, the climate for 
technical development has much greater significance for the 
technical renewal. 
  17. The long-range stability in government regulations, the 
interest rate level and the taxation and fee policy are three 
areas of particular importance for the climate of technical 
development in the energy field. It is further essential--which 
does not distinguish the energy field from other fields of 
technology--that there is a great deal of expertise in basic 
research and education and an economic policy which stimulates 
industrial activity. 
  18. Innovation support for companies has been given in three 
forms: regulation, financial means of control, and information. 
Regulations have been the traditional method to reduce the 
environmental consequences of technology application. In some 
cases taxes and other fees have been used for this purpose. 
Financial contributions have been the most common method for 
supporting certain technology developments. Tax relief has 
sometimes been used. Information has been sparingly used as 
innovation support. 
  19. Financial contributions for development projects have 
possibly in some cases accelerated an ongoing development 
process. In all, however, this support has not had any 
appreciable effects, neither positive nor negative, on the 
activity of the companies. 
  20. Taxes and fees, as well as regulations, have in general 
had much greater effect, but not always of the kind intended. 
  21. There are three main types of principal difficulties 
involving social support for the development of energy 
technology. The project selection fails for reasons of expertise 
and politics, the support is often not sufficiently 
long-lasting, or it has a negative impact on the natural 
innovation tendency in the companies. 
  22. By tradition, R&amp;D results have rapidly spread 
between the 
energy companies. The "marketization" which is under way could 
lead to a slower distribution of results and to more parallel 
work among enterprises. This should be opposed by reinforcing 
joint industry research. 
  23. Historically, the energy companies, and particularly the 
players in the "technology triangle," have been marked by a 
willingness to take technical risks when this was in line with 
the companies' strategic considerations. In principle this still 
applies. The sector is characterized by large companies with 
good opportunities for financing R&amp;D efforts. There is 
therefore 
no reason to assume that the energy companies in general are 
underinvesting in R&amp;D. 
  24. Steering the use of technology toward increasingly 
environmentally adapted technology is an essential social task. 
For that reason it is important that the environmental cost 
aspect is incorporated into the thinking. Regulations have often 
been more effective than environmental fees, which is likely to 
be due mostly to the fees having been exploited as an 
opportunity for taxation. These efforts must be credible, stable 
and as far as possible, undertaken in international cooperation. 
<H5>  1. Content and Organization </H5>
  This study analyzes how society should act in order to 
stimulate commercial development of energy technology. By 
commercial technical development is meant development, which 
from a shorter or longer perspective is aimed at methods, 
products or processes used in the market. 
  In Chapter 2 the technical development process, the forces 
behind it and the factors for success are analyzed. The 
objective is to answer the question: What determines the success 
for technical development projects and new technology, and to 
what extent is energy technology and the development of energy 
technology different from other technology development? 
  Technical development is also affected by factors of the 
surrounding world such as the companies' historical decisions, 
market development, competitors' actions, etc. In Chapter 3 the 
question is therefore asked: What has governed the orientation 
of energy technology development, and what are the effects of 
the structure and organization of the energy sector on this 
technical development? Also discussed in the chapter are ongoing 
and anticipated changes and their possible impact on the future 
development of energy technology. 
  Chapter 4 discusses society's role in the development of 
energy technology and the historical experience from government 
measures in Sweden and abroad. The main question is to what 
extent and in which ways society can influence the development 
of energy technology, and what the experiences of these measures 
are. 
  In Chapter 5, in conclusion, proposals are stated for the 
way 
society can stimulate commercial development of energy 
technology. The organization of the study is shown by the figure 
below [not included]: 
  In addition to the working group's own experience and 
evaluations, the study is based on three specialist seminars 
with about 15 invited theoreticians and practitioners. The 
seminars dealt with the issues discussed in Chapters 2, 3 and 4, 
respectively. 
  For each of these seminars a foundation report was worked 
out 
as supporting material. The reports from the first and third 
seminar, respectively, are given in Supplements 1 and 2 to this 
partial study, while the foundation for the second seminar forms 
its own report (AF, 1991). 
<H5>  2. What Characterizes Successful Energy Technology? </H5>
  In this chapter will be discussed future factors of success 
for technical development projects, factors which affect the 
speed of distribution for a new technology, as well as what 
distinguishes development of energy technology from other 
technical development. 
<H3>  2.1 What Characterizes Successful Technical Development 
Projects? </H3>
  By technical development projects is meant the entire 
process 
from idea to commercial product, by way of R&amp;D, product 
development, product adaptation, etc. A successful project is a 
project which leads to a product that sooner or later will 
generate profit. 
  Technical development is usually divided into basic 
research, 
applied research, production, demonstration and the distribution 
of the technology in the market. One often talks about the so- 
called development chain. The goal of basic research is internal 
scientific theory formation, and basic research has an intrinsic 
value, while other R&amp;D activities, in the shorter or longer 
term, are aimed at producing methods, products or production 
processes. It is often taken for granted that all the phases in 
the "development chain" must be passed through for technical 
development. This is not the case. Research is not a necessary 
first step for product development. Not even production 
development is always necessary for technical development. 
Learning effects which lead to technical development also occur 
in connection with undertaking other work. The last step, 
introducing the technology to the market, however, is a 
condition for the technology having an impact on society and 
thus leading to technical development in the actual sense. Thus, 
successful product development must lead to market-tested 
products and processes from which the technology developer as 
well as the buyer makes money. 
  The orientation toward results in product development leads 
to a difference in how research and development work. In 
commercial development work the effort is rapidly and 
effectively to achieve results. It may be said that research 
strives to talk about how something works. In product 
development, it is enough to know that it works, without for 
that reason having complete knowledge of why it happens this 
way. If difficulties occur in product development, there are two 
possibilities: "going around" the problems or compromising the 
performance characteristics of the product. Many elegant 
technical solutions involve precisely "going around" the 
difficulties. A good example of this from the case studies (see 
Supplement 1) is the HVDC [High Voltage-Direct Current] case, in 
which one actually never succeeded in solving the problem of the 
"backfiring" of the gas-filled rectifiers but it was still 
possible to use them as rectifiers by creating enough 
redundance. It is not very common that one succeeds by doing so, 
of course. Most usual is that one is forced to compromise with 
the performance of the product. 
  Often, it also turns out that in a certain phase it is not 
enough to know that the product works, but one has to know the 
physical foundations in greater detail in order to continue. 
This requires research and means that the course of development 
comes to a halt while waiting for these findings. 
  In principle, development projects can be divided into 
development of new generations of existing products and 
genuinely new development products of strategic importance for 
the future. A generational change is aimed at retaining 
positions in the marketplace and is the company's way of 
increasing competitive strength and profitability in the short 
run. Often, it turns out that by changing generations it is 
possible to reduce manufacturing costs or increase performance 
by up to 20 percent. New development projects mean strategic 
investments for the future, and it takes time before these 
investments become profitable. 
  In the meantime it is necessary for established products to 
generate profits ("cash cows") which can be used for the new 
development. Consequently, both types of projects must exist 
simultaneously, and a successful company thus works for both the 
long term and the short term at the same time. 
  The following section deals mainly with new development 
projects, although part of the reasoning can be applied to 
generational change projects. 
  Financial volume and development times vary greatly between 
various projects, product fields and types of technology. In the 
energy sector, as in other sectors of infrastructure character, 
the development is dominated by large projects and facilities 
with long technical and economic life. 
  The development costs for new technology are difficult to 
indicate precisely. Figures often include a great deal more than 
direct development costs and must always be treated with 
caution. The type of development processes which are described 
in Supplement 1, however, often involve direct development costs 
in the range of several hundred million kronor and up, usually 
followed by even higher costs for the first reference facility. 
  Figure 2.1 [not included] shows the time from idea to 
commercial product for 45 important innovations in Sweden during 
the postwar era. As can be seen in the figure, the times vary 
greatly around an average number of about eight years. Energy 
innovations are among the areas marked by long development 
times. Hence, it is not unusual to have development times of 
more than 10 years. 
  Distributing the technology in the market also proceeds 
relatively slowly, and perhaps for that reason it takes another 
approximately 10 years before the product has paid off its 
development costs. Such development courses naturally pose major 
demands for long-term involvement and financial stamina by the 
companies and, accordingly, require financially strong 
businesses. 
  Since the ultimate evaluation of whether the project was 
actually successful or not often cannot be undertaken until 
close to 20 years after the project idea, it is necessary when 
starting a development project to be assured that in the future 
the project will lead to financial and competitive advantages 
for the company. 
  The combination of high costs and long time frames have the 
result that the future profitability of the projects must be 
very high. Covering the cost of the project is therefore not 
enough of an incentive for the company to put its best 
development resources into a project. 
  The product development process can be divided into two 
phases: The search phase, in which a rather free search of 
alternative methods is made in order to solve problems and the 
product specification developed. In all, the search phase can 
consume up to 10 percent of the total development resources. 
After that, the development project itself ends. 
  The success factors[.sup]1[/] for a technical development 
project are many and the interplay between them is not always 
simple. Often it turns out, however, that successful technical 
development projects are marked by a chain of successes 
consisting of: 


    -  Early evaluations and high-quality assessments, which 
leads to 
  -  a clear and early picture of the market and the product's 
properties, which leads to 
  -  a strong product, which leads to 
  -  good market penetration. 

    One usually talks about "protocol" in the development work. 
With the "protocol" concept the entire development work is aimed 
correctly from the beginning, and this usually leads to a strong 
product. 
  All projects always include knowledge from outside. In 
Figure 
2.2 [not included] is shown a typology of various such methods 
for acquiring ideas and knowledge. It is thus not possible, 
necessary or desirable always to generate all knowledge oneself. 
Many insist that Swedish companies and Sweden on the whole have 
been particularly successful as regards acquiring knowledge from 
the surrounding world and converting it into new products and 
processes of their own. something which is particularly 
important for a small country. 
  The key to a successful development project is therefore to 
make the correct evaluations immediately in the initial phase. 
In order to do so, it is necessary to have a good and early 
product and system specification, which properly points out what 
market there is or can be expected and how to deal with it. The 
basic question is "When and how will the product be 
competitive?". On those occasions when the problem description 
(or problem definition) was lacking, was insufficient or even 
wrong, the projects usually failed. 
  The most common reason for such failure is that the market 
connection has been too weak. Experience from similar product 
development work provides better opportunities. Of course, the 
preconditions for successful evaluations increase if one has 
good knowledge of the customer of his needs. 
  A generally accepted truth is that new customers (new 
markets) are more difficult than new products (new technology) 
and the combination of new products and new customers is close 
to hopelessly difficult. This is because coupling the 
development to the market becomes considerably more difficult in 
this case. Well developed cooperation with the customer, with a 
knowledgeable potential customer, automatically leads to being 
able to enter marketing aspects into the development work and 
thus to being able to position the development work correctly 
from the beginning and increasing the opportunities for a good 
product. 
  At the same time as we earlier concluded that it is 
essential 
to have sufficient resources for development work, it is often 
not an advantage to have too many resources. Particularly not in 
the initial phase of development projects. This could lead to 
becoming careless with identifying the goal of the development 
work, which means that the development project is less well 
positioned and therefore leads to a poorer result. Once the 
search phase is concluded and the development project itself 
starts, it is often a major advantage to have large resources. 
Particularly for products with short production lives, the 
product must be quickly developed. This is facilitated by being 
able to pursue the development with parallel development paths, 
something which requires major resources. 
  As was stated above, successful development projects are 
often marked by close cooperation between the developer of the 
technology and an early, potential customer. In several of the 
case studies in Supplement 1, it is striking that there was 
considerable willingness to take risks by someone or both 
parties in the development work. Even in very large development 
projects this willingness to take risk can often be traced to 
some person or a small group of persons in leading positions. 
Without these "entrepreneurs" or "fiery souls," technical 
innovations do not proceed. It is essential to note, which can 
also be seen in the case studies, that the entrepreneur does not 
intrinsically need to be directly involved in the development 
work, but can very well be an early customer. 
  The incentive for the entrepreneur is usually the hope for 
financial profit, of course, and for that reason it is important 
for tax regulations, etc. to be designed in such a way that the 
entrepreneur has a clear financial incentive. 
<H5>  2.2 Spreading New Technology in the Market </H5>
  One proven experience is that Sweden has been successful not 
only in gathering R&amp;D experience from the rest of the world 
but 
also regarding rapid spreading of technology. This applies to 
the energy sector as well. 
  The factors which affect the success of a technology in the 
market naturally depend to a large extent on what leads to a 
successful development project. Well-developed, early 
cooperation with the customer appears to be the most important 
individual factor in this case as well. This means that many 
difficulties are automatically avoided. At the same time, the 
lack of such early customer cooperation means that so many 
difficulties accumulate that the product will scarcely succeed 
in the market. 
  New technology is often introduced in connection with new 
investments. If new technology is to achieve good distribution, 
it must therefore be available when the customer group has a 
need for new investments. This is particularly important for 
technology that cannot be applied to existing facilities, which 
is often the case for process technology. 
  In a growing market capacity must be expanded, while with 
zero growth new investments need only to be undertaken at the 
rate old facilities are taken out of operation. That makes 
spreading new technology much more rapid during strong market 
growth. The fact that nuclear power was able to achieve such 
rapid distribution in the Swedish energy system was made easier, 
for example, because the penetration took place in a market 
under rapid growth. Correspondingly, a strong structural 
reorganization leads to major opportunities for new technology. 
The rapid distribution processes which are provided in the case 
descriptions for the TMP [Thermo-Mechanical Pulp] process and 
the steel development in Supplement 1 should at least in part be 
seen in the light of the rapid structural change which occurred 
within these industries at the same time. These two sample cases 
also show that even in capital-intensive, mature, industries new 
technology can spread remarkably quickly, if suitable conditions 
prevail. 
  If investment willingness is low, the speed of distribution 
for new technology is usually slow. This will be the case during 
slow market growth, for example. This slow distribution is 
particularly striking in connection with a transition from a 
growth situation to a non-growth situation, when for a period 
replacement investments will be particularly small as a result 
of a relatively modern physical plant structure. 
  The most important individual property for the market 
penetration of the product, given that a need for the product 
exists, is the advantages offered by the product relative to 
previous products. Since business activity imposes demands for 
"measurability," the improvement, at least as regards producer 
goods, must be financially or technically measurable in the form 
of improved product performance or lower costs. Thus, it is not 
enough for the product to "be perceived" as better. 
  The course of the distribution is also affected by the 
product's compatibility with existing norms, standards and 
technical environment. Market penetration takes longer for 
technology which does not fit existing systems, technically or 
organizationally, or which, by being radically different or 
complex, are perceived as foreign by the customers. 
  The opportunity to test the technology on a reasonable scale 
also affects the course of the distribution. Technology 
involving technical risks which must be taken in facilities 
which are felt to be large by those involved have greater 
difficulties than where the technical risk has been dealt with 
in a comparatively small pilot facility. 
  One factor which in the case studies appears important for 
spreading the technology is the reference facility. Very high 
demands for accessibility of the products are often placed on 
process technology. At the same time, new investment has 
consequences far into the future. The result of this is that a 
buyer of such technology feels healthy caution toward untested 
technical solutions. It is therefore essential for distribution 
to build an initial, moderately large reference facility on a 
commercial basis, bought by a respected customer, known for 
being a good purchaser. Such a facility is important for the 
continued technical evaluation but still more important for 
making commercial evaluation easier for new customers. A 
demonstration facility not built on a commercial basis is of 
limited value, however. Although it could possibly show that the 
technology works, it does not facilitate the customers' 
commercial assessment in the same way. 
<H5>  2.3 Distinguishing Factors for Developing Energy Technology </H5>
  The factors of success in the previous section are mainly 
general, independent of the technical field. In this section is 
discussed to what extent the development of energy technology 
differs from other technical development. After that, the 
characteristics for cable-transmitted energy technology and the 
special consequences for those development patterns are 
discussed. This is because the development of energy technology 
in Sweden to a large extent involved cable-transmitted 
technology and technical components or systems which operated 
within the framework of cable grids. 
  What Characterizes the Development of Energy 
Technology? 
  Energy technology has many similarities with other process 
industry: 


    -  it requires large, initial investments 
  -  it leads to strong relationships of dependence between the 
energy supplier and the energy user 
  -  it poses special demands for careful production planning 
since 
the maximum production capacity is greatly limited, and 
  -  it poses particularly great demands on accessibility in the 
systems. 

    All in all, this results in the energy system having a 
considerable, built-in "inertia" against technical changes. 
Radical change of the architecture of the energy system is a 
process which ranges of several decades, while such a 
development in some other fields can be considerably faster. The 
development times for producing new technologies and processes 
are also comparatively long, which further reinforces the "long 
perspective" in energy technology development. 
  The special market structure with a few equipment 
manufacturers and energy suppliers is to some extent a result of 
the chosen technology. Only strong companies with considerable 
financial stamina and extensive technical know-how can cope with 
large, long-term projects of high technical complexity and large 
financial scope. This structure, in turn, has created special 
preconditions for long-range, close cooperation. The customers 
have known that there were supplier companies with a great deal 
of ability to satisfy their wishes. At the same time the 
supplier companies have met strong customers, often with stable 
social support, who have been able to risk a failed project 
without too much problem. The energy companies, between 
themselves, have also been marked by a striking openness, which 
is facilitated, of course, by the fact that there was no 
competitive situation. Historically, the development of energy 
technology is therefore characterized by having been conducted 
in an unusually cooperative environment and by market relations 
of a particularly lasting nature. 
  Something which distinguishes the energy field from several 
other fields with correspondingly high proportions of capital 
costs, such as the telecommunications field, is that the 
development of the operating costs, in this case the development 
of fuel costs, has turned out to be of decisive importance for 
the profitability of the investments. This is due to the very 
large fluctuations in raw material prices and taxes. 
  Of course, the energy field also differs because both 
technology and marketing questions have been affected by 
political decisions to a greater extent than in other areas of 
technology. This is true both in Sweden and in several other 
countries. It is also connected with the fact that society has 
quite favorable opportunities for influencing the development 
because of the close involvement of the energy sector with 
environmental and resource issues, and because society in 
several countries has been directly involved as owner in one or 
more of the energy companies, as well as the importance of this 
for the social development. 
  The Effects of Cable-Transmitted Technology on 
Development Patterns 
  A cable-transmitted energy system poses particularly high 
demands on the development in a number of respects. 
  A cable-transmitted system creates an even stronger 
dependence between supplier and customer. The customer has 
become dependent on an energy-supplying link and cannot easily 
change supplier if he is not satisfied. The supplier is also 
greatly dependent on his customers, since the investment made 
cannot be changed with ease. The customers are not quite as 
dependent on just one supplier, but can change to someone else 
if the cooperation is not working. The suppliers can also change 
the circle of customers during the lifetime of the investment. 
  Since the investment in a cable grid has a very long life 
and 
has the character of a "sunk cost" when it is completed, it has 
impact far into the future. The investment will thus affect the 
future scope of action. 
  In a cable-transmitted system it is not only on the 
production side that it is very important to have even 
utilization. It is just as important for utilization in the 
distribution system to be even, partly because the large amount 
of capital invested should be efficiently utilized, and partly 
because the maximum transmission capability is more limited than 
in a non-cable- conducted system. After all, there are 
ordinarily no possibilities of employing extra transmission 
capacity, as in the case of a non-cable-transmitted system. 
  Furthermore, there is usually not any storage possibility 
corresponding to the one in non-cable-transmitted systems. 
Production must take place at the same time as consumption, 
which is in some contrast to the effort for even utilization of 
the system and makes optimization extra difficult. This leads to 
cable-transmitted energy systems being marked by particularly 
large advantages of scale. By building large systems and 
coupling together production units and users with different 
characteristics, it is possible to achieve the desired balance 
at the same time as variations on both the production and the 
utilization side can be dealt with. 
  In sum, the factors mentioned above have the effect that the 
energy technology which is part of cable-transmitted 
distribution systems operates under special development 
circumstances. 
  At the same time it must be stated that there are 
differences 
in degree between cable-transmitted systems which are due to the 
fundamental architecture of the systems. In this case it is 
possible to distinguish between cable-transmitted systems on the 
one hand, which are first established locally in order later to 
be coupled into an integrated grid, and, on the other hand, 
entirely new structures which can be directly combined into an 
integrated grid. A system which is built locally and then 
integrated involves fewer initial investments but often, in the 
long run, poorer development possibilities than a system 
established from the beginning. 
<H5>  3. The Technical Development Within the Energy Industry </H5>
  The following chapter analyzes development patterns for the 
Swedish energy system. 
  After a brief description of the power and heating industry 
and its supplying industry and its structure, in section 3.2 we 
will discuss development patterns for the Swedish energy system 
and the development of the Swedish energy technology. In the 
concluding section we will analyze certain current development 
patterns as well as important future questions for the 
development of energy technology. 
<H5>  3.1 The Structure of the Energy Industry </H5>
  An energy system includes three principal types of players. 
Energy suppliers, energy users and equipment manufacturers, who 
deliver technical equipment to suppliers and users. While the 
energy suppliers and equipment manufacturers are clearly 
identifiable groups, the energy users are a heterogeneous crowd, 
which includes everything from very large customers, such as a 
steel mill, down to private persons. In the following 
description, interest is focused partly on the supplying 
industry and equipment manufacturers, and partly on the heating 
and electric power industry. 
  Producers of power and heat (meaning the power companies and 
the municipal power plants) in 1990 had a turnover of about 65 
billion kronor and employed about 20,000 persons (AF, 1991). 
This is somewhat less than the pulp and paper industry (73 
billion kronor) and automobile industry (77 billion kronor), but 
is, for example, more than three times more than the turnover in 
the telecommunications industry (23 billion kronor) and seven 
times more than the pharmaceutical industry (9.3 billion kronor). 
  Judged by the number of employees, the automobile industry 
is 
nearly three times larger, the pulp and paper industry twice as 
large and the telecommunications industry approximately the same 
size as the power and heating industry. The pharmaceutical 
industry has about one-third as many employees. The turnover per 
employee is therefore more than twice as high among power and 
heat producers as in the already very capital-intensive pulp and 
paper industry and nearly four times higher than in the 
telecommunications industry. A distinctive feature of the energy 
industry is thus an almost extremely high capital intensity. 
  Of the Swedish power production capacity Vattenfall owns 50 
percent, the industry 25 percent, the municipalities 19 percent 
and others six percent (applies to 1991). In comparison with 
other countries the ownership of the electric power production 
is well balanced between government, municipal and private 
interests. The power industry, and of course the municipal power 
plants as well, have traditionally been of an almost totally 
national character with a low degree of internationalization. 
Traditionally, there also has never been any extensive foreign 
ownership interest. A certain internationalization and greater 
international ownership has taken place in the last few years. 
The obstacles to entering the industry are high. Traditionally, 
legislation and concessions have in many cases made starting new 
businesses impossible. Although this is not the case, the 
opportunities for new establishment are comparatively small as a 
result of the very large investments required in many areas. 
  There are about 300 companies which distribute electric 
power 
in the country. The 10 largest power distributors have 37 
percent of Sweden's total subscribers. The largest distributors 
are Sydkraft, Stockholm Energi, Vattenfall and Goteborg Energi. 
  During the period 1970-1990 power consumption more than 
doubled in Sweden, from 63 Twh/year to 140 Twh/year (including 
transmission losses). This means an average rate of increase of 
more than 4 percent per year. Distributed over the period, the 
increase from 1970 to 1975 was a total of 26 percent, 1975-1980 
a total of 18 percent, 1980-1985 a total of 39 percent and 1985- 
1990 a total of seven percent. At present the growth is lower. 
  Just as the electric power industry, the district heating 
industry can be divided into a production segment and a 
distribution segment. In most cases a vertical integration 
exists between producer and distributor, which is why that 
division is not as obvious. District heat is delivered from hot 
water centers and thermal power plants. Characteristic of the 
industry is that there is major variation in size. The 10 
largest plants are responsible for about 50 percent of the 
district heat deliveries. The 100 smallest plants (about 
two-thirds of the number of plants) only represent about 15 
percent. The typical owner of a district heating grid and 
production facility is a municipality or a municipally-owned 
corporation. The largest suppliers of district heat in Sweden 
are Stockholm Energi, Goteborg Energi, Malmo Energi, Vasteras 
Tekniska Verken and Uppsala Energi. 
  District heat was expanded quite rapidly during the 1970's 
and the first half of the 1980's. No significant market growth 
can be foreseen at present outside the larger cities, since most 
areas suitable for district heating grids have already been 
utilized. 
  Several Swedish companies in the heavy mechanical 
engineering 
and electrical engineering industry have established their 
strength on the basis of delivering equipment to energy 
facilities. The dominant company, particularly in electrical 
engineering, has of course been ASEA/ABB. ABB companies 
operating in Sweden are big on light-water reactors, steam 
turbines, generators, high-voltage transmission equipment, 
switching gear, transformers, electric motors, control 
equipment, stack gas purification equipment, in order just to 
mention some of the most important product fields. 
  For delivery of large energy production components, such as 
furnaces or turbines, there are only a few suppliers in Sweden. 
When it comes to traditional steam boilers for power plants, 
there are no longer any manufacturers under Swedish ownership in 
Sweden. Suppliers for the Swedish market are, among others, ABB, 
AEG, Ahlstrom, Kvaerner and Siemens. 
  For smaller equipment details within the energy industry, 
such as transformers, switching equipment, valves, pumps, etc. 
there are several suppliers, of whom a few foreign ones, such as 
Siemens, also have a small production in Sweden. 
<H3>  3.2 What Characterizes the Swedish Development of Energy 
Technology? </H3>
  The development of energy technology in Sweden in several 
respects equals the technical development in the electric power 
sector. By that is not meant that the development has solely 
involved electrical engineering, but that the development was 
undertaken with a view toward the needs of the electrical 
sector. This emphasis can be traced to the establishment of the 
energy system and to the composition of Swedish industry. 
  For a long time Swedish industrial development was mostly 
equivalent to the development of basic industry. The principal 
task of the energy sector became to supply this trade of such 
vital importance to Sweden with sufficient quantities of 
sufficiently cheap energy. Gradually, a considerable mechanical 
engineering industry also appeared, which, to be sure, did not 
require large amounts of energy but nevertheless depended on an 
assured supply primarily of electric power. Guaranteed 
deliveries of sufficient amounts of electric power at 
competitive prices thus quickly became a condition for the 
ability of the initially strongly export-oriented Swedish 
industry to compete. This required a strong power industry. 
  At the beginning of the century the supply and use of 
electricity was local. With increasing demand greater capacity 
was needed. The power industry realized at an early stage that 
the special Swedish situation with major natural resources, 
located in completely different places than the consumption 
centers, would be able to provide unique opportunities for 
solving the electric power supply in a rational and 
cost-effective way. There was talk during this period of "the 
white coal" (that is to say hydroelectric power) and how it 
could be utilized. 
  The technology to do so was not available, however. The 
powerful need for development created expansion opportunities 
for the Swedish electrical engineering industry headed by ASEA. 
This development provided basic technical know-how and player 
relationships which could be used as a foundation when the 
expansion of hydroelectric power was completed and other 
technical systems were needed to meet the constantly growing 
need for electricity. The establishment of the nuclear power 
industry, above all, is an example of this. 
  The typical pattern for the development of the Swedish 
energy 
technology has therefore been that technology was developed in 
order to meet needs within the Swedish energy system. These 
products, and the knowledge and expertise which have accumulated 
in the tracks of this development, have then in several cases 
become internationally successful products. Some outstanding 
examples of this are, for example, ASEA's high-voltage 
transmission equipment, for alternating current as well as for 
direct current, turbines, primarily from ASEA STAL, and ASEA 
ATOM's nuclear reactors. 
  One may speak about there being a "technology triangle" 
between ASEA/ABB and the power companies (primarily Sydkraft and 
Vattenfall) and the electricity-intensive industry (chiefly the 
pulp and paper industry and the iron and steel industry). It is 
in the interface between these industries that development needs 
and technical know-how have been found, so that meaningful 
development cooperations could be established. Large projects 
which involve long-term commitments and have long repayment 
periods pose major demands on careful coordination. The result 
of this is that technology development is made easier by a 
guarantor, who assures the long-range involvement of the 
parties. Several of the development projects are marked by the 
existence of such a guarantor. The relationships are explained 
by the figure below [not included]. 
  The development has often assumed the character of 
development cooperations and has often taken place under 
businesslike forms, in which the roles of the various players 
were clear and expressed. The fact that precisely Swedish 
players cooperated therefore is not due to any forced Swedish 
protectionism, but to the fact that it was actually more 
rational. 
  There are several examples of this type of development 
cooperation in Sweden, even outside the field of 
energy[.sup]2[/], and Dahmen has coined the expression 
development blocks to describe similar processes in his study of 
the Swedish industrial development during the period between the 
wars (Dahmen, 1950). 
  In certain cases these development blocks consisted directly 
of cooperation between a couple of companies. The cooperation 
between ASEA and Vattenfall regarding high-voltage technology 
represents such an example. An important and well-known example 
in which a guarantor facilitated the development is Stockholms 
Enskilda Bank's activity at the beginning of the century, when 
the bank through favorable credits facilitated the expansion of 
hydroelectric power and greatly participated in establishing 
ASEA as a company (Gasslander, 1956). Nuclear power represents a 
clear example of a development block in which close cooperation 
between several players, different ones at different times, 
brought the development forward. For nuclear power the state 
assumed an essential role as a guarantor in order to make the 
development easier. Even in recent times there are examples that 
such development blocks have originated. The foremost example is 
the development of large heat pumps, in which ASEA STAL and the 
municipal thermal power plants, by acting with foresight, were 
rapidly able to preserve the potential of the heat pump in the 
district heating grids. 
  The development of new technology has not been wholly 
concentrated to the technology triangle, of course. But the 
Swedish energy sector must still be said to be characterized by 
the fact that it includes strong and weak partial sectors from 
the aspect of development. By developmentally weak partial 
industries we mean that they tends to underinvest in technical 
development as a result of a lack of incentive. The usual 
opinion is that primarily the construction sector and the 
municipal energy plants represent these developmentally weak 
sectors. 
  In the construction sector these problems are on the product 
side. The problem has not been general, but was mainly linked to 
the multi-family dwelling sector. Technical development was 
undertaken in order to meet stiff and rigid product standards 
rather than actual product development needs. In combination 
with a nearly insatiable demand for the products, the 
development pressure was thus very low. The reduced regulatory 
control which now marks the construction sector, in combination 
with a more normalized demand which leads to greater 
competition, can be expected to increase the incentives for 
development in the future. This is demonstrated above all by the 
experience in the small housing sector, where competitive 
pressure has been higher and development more favorable. New 
building standards resulted in electrical power during the past 
10 years being the only financially justifiable alternative in 
small houses. The fact that electric heat was installed in turn 
resulted in the market having introduced an insulating standard 
at a higher level than prescribed by the standards. The 
development in the small housing sector shows that the market 
functions even as regards more efficient energy if provided with 
favorable opportunities. Not even in the construction process 
itself have there been any corresponding tendencies toward 
underinvestment. On the contrary; Swedish companies were 
responsible for a considerable part of the international 
technical development involving the construction process. 
  That the municipal power plants represented a 
developmentally 
weak industry is primarily explained by the fact that there were 
weak owners. The owners were influenced by interest groups which 
wanted the municipal energy plant to keep the rates as low as 
possible in the short run, which necessarily created 
difficulties for the companies in undertaking projects of an 
R&amp;D 
nature, which in the short term predominantly mean higher costs 
for the company. This tendency was reinforced by the ample 
support which was given. The investment patterns have changed, 
so that the government had to put up a significant part of the 
costs. Without the subsidies the owners would most likely have 
had to assume greater responsibility for the companies' 
development, so that the presence of financial development 
subsidies contributed to a poorer development than what would 
otherwise have been the case. 
<H5>  3.3 Why Did the Development Turn Out This Way? </H5>
  A few factors seem particularly important in order to 
explain 
the development: 


    -  The development of the market 
  -  the interplay and relationships between the various players 
  -  the conditions of the surrounding world. 

    It is in this connection essential to distinguish between 
the 
earlier development, up to the mid-1970's, and the changes which 
have occurred since then. 
  The Earlier Development 
  The lasting, strong growth in energy, and particularly 
electricity, consumption created a powerful need for new 
capacity. This opened up major market opportunities for 
innovative companies. The rapid growth also reduced the 
investment risk for the power companies. In that strong growth 
situation it was not a direct catastrophe for a company in a 
monopolistic situation if capacity "happened" to be expanded 
somewhat to quickly. After only a few years new demand 
developed, which caused the facility to be needed. 
  Regarding the player structure, it can be noted that 
cooperation has taken place between quite large companies and 
that there have been close relationships and major confidence in 
one another's capability. Accordingly, one has been convinced 
that the problems could actually be solved, and if any project 
were to fail, contrary to expectations, the parties would manage 
to accept financial failure without insurmountable difficulties. 
At the same time it was obvious that the buyer side would assume 
some of the risks with the development work.[.sup]3[/] 
  It should also be noted that there was strong government 
involvement as support for this development. Other than in 
exceptional cases, the support did not affect technical or 
commercial questions but meant that the players could anticipate 
that the rules of the game in the cooperation would not 
drastically change during the course of the work. The companies 
could thus use long depreciation periods for new investments, 
since one was acting in a politically and market-wise very 
stable environment. The government also influenced the 
development through the heavily regulated credit market, since 
there were low nominal interest rates and there was plenty of 
capital because of the extensive public savings, for example. 
  The Later Development 
  During the most recent 20-year period, the conditions for 
energy technology have gradually changed. Market opportunities 
have changed both for the industrial and the energy companies. 
The costs of technical development have also risen. 
  An often represented view is that Swedish industry has 
become 
more short-sighted during the 1970's and 1980's. It is quite 
clear that over the more recent 25-year period the majority of 
industrial companies has encountered a faster pace of change in 
the surrounding world, including, for example, more rapid market 
changes and greater international competition. As a reaction to 
this greater pace of change in the rest of the world, in the 
late 1960's an altered leadership philosophy emerged within the 
manufacturing industry. Quarterly balance sheets, 
divisionalization and profit units created more pressure on 
company managements always to show a good result. The trend was 
reinforced by the wave of incorporations and dispersions of 
ownership during the 1980's. In all, this development has been 
favorable by creating greater pressure on company managements to 
work more actively with the firms' development, but at the same 
time it has, of course, heightened interest in the company's 
short-term goals. Greater concentration on short-term issues 
does not, however, as has sometimes been indicated, necessarily 
mean lower efficiency in the long term. If the surrounding world 
has changed, it is necessary to undertake measures against or 
adjust to these changes. At the same time there is obviously 
risk that focusing on the long term, which is also necessary for 
the company's long-range success, may be neglected in this 
process. 
  The energy companies also faced a less predictable future 
during this period. The energy price fluctuations had been a 
constant problem since the beginning of the 1970's. The price 
fluctuations were reinforced by the effects caused by varying 
taxes and environmental fees. Often there were also subsidies 
available for new investments, which further increased the 
uncertainty about the cost of various alternatives. Add to this 
the political uncertainty about the future of nuclear power, 
which meant that there was some risk that 50 percent of the 
electric power production capacity would need replacement in the 
short term. 
  As for the market development, the 1970's represented a 
clearly lower rate of growth. According to the official energy 
statistics, the energy consumption even decreased.[.sup]4[/] 
In the early 1980's the simultaneous economic boom, conversion 
to electric heat, and the expansion of the district heating 
grids led to rapid market growth in both the electric power and 
heating sector. On the electric power side, this development 
was, of course, facilitated by the fact that new nuclear power 
plants rapidly entered the system in the late 1970's and early 
1980's. The rate of growth in recent years, even regardless of 
the effect of the economic conditions, has decreased as a result 
of greater energy efficiency and the fact that conversion to 
electric and district heating has halted. This limited growth 
has not required new production capacity to any major extent, 
and new investments during the second half of the 1980's have 
been very limited, in the area of power as well as of heating. 
  The higher interest rate situation has also had a major 
impact in the direction of projects with a short period of 
repayment. This applies to both industrial and energy companies. 
  The opportunities for technology development have also 
changed. Swedish reference facilities and operating experience 
have been very important for the further commercialization of 
new technology. A certain change has occurred, however, which 
can be exemplified by the dominant company in the field in 
Sweden, ABB. Sweden is still an important domestic market for 
the majority of ABB companies active in Sweden, of course. 
However, during the 1970's and 1980's an internationalization of 
the electrical engineering industry took place, which resulted 
in Sweden no longer having the same character of "springboard to 
the world" for ABB as was the case for ASEA. Previously, the 
company essentially searched out development problems in Sweden 
and developed products for the Swedish market, which were then 
adapted for other markets. Nowadays, the technical development 
in the electrical engineering industry takes place for the 
international market, and the Swedish market no longer occupies 
the same special position. The corresponding development also 
applies to many other companies, small as well as large, which 
are active in the infrastructure field.[.sup]5[/] 
  One driving force behind this development has been higher 
development costs as a result of increasingly advanced and 
complex technical systems, which means that the development 
costs must be distributed over a larger market. That provides 
increasingly fewer opportunities for special national solutions 
in markets which are comparatively small, such as the Swedish 
one. Another important driving force in Sweden is that the 
combination of lower market growth and a modern establishment 
structure has meant that there was no need for new facilities 
after the introduction of nuclear power. This forced the 
industrial companies to direct their eyes even more toward the 
needs of the surrounding world. Altogether, this has the result 
that there is increasingly less relevance in speaking of 
specifically Swedish technology development in the energy field. 
It applies to a particularly high degree in the electric power 
sector. The same development trends can also be noticed in the 
heating sector, however, although this development is somewhat 
later in time as a result of generally lower development costs 
and a larger domestic market. 
  All the factors given above contributed to the generation of 
fewer long-range development projects in Sweden in the energy 
field over the past 10-15 years, compared to what was previously 
the case. 
<H5>  3.4 Development Trends for the Future </H5>
  In this section will be discussed development trends and 
their potential effects on the technical development. Just as 
all other predictions for the future, these must be treated with 
caution. 
  There are a number of indications that both the electric 
power and the heating market in Sweden and in our immediate 
environment face a historical break with the trend. Even if 
industrial growth during the 1990's will be good, which is 
desirable, it is likely that the growth in energy consumption 
will be of limited extent. At the same time the physical plant 
structure is relatively modern and, particularly in the area of 
electric power, a certain increase in demand could be met by 
increasing output from existing facilities. The greater European 
integration of electricity systems simultaneously leads to more 
efficient utilization of existing reserves and for that reason 
they can be shrunk from an overall point of view. In general, 
this argues for a limited need for new construction of power and 
thermal facilities for quite a long time, at least 10 years, 
which has a considerable impact on the penetration of new 
technology, especially against the background of the modern 
facility structure. Remodeling, for example as a result of 
stricter environmental requirements, and current maintenance and 
modernizations will take place, but these are measures of 
comparatively limited extent. 
  New investments could, of course, occur even over a shorter 
time frame, in that case probably for reasons of competition in 
the wake of the now ongoing regulation. If a more extensive 
export market for electric power should develop, this could also 
lead to new investments. 
  Nuclear power still represents an uncertainty factor, of 
course, with considerable consequences for the plans by the 
energy companies, since it will affect the time at which new 
production capacity will be needed. If nuclear power is to be 
abolished by the year 2010, very extensive new construction will 
have to be started within a 10-year period, while more extensive 
replacement investments can otherwise wait. Since new technology 
is introduced in connection with new investments, and nuclear 
power abolition will lead to a forced investment wave, the 
opportunities for rapid spreading of new technology will be 
greater if nuclear power is abolished. That this is the case 
should not be interpreted as this report advocating such 
abolition. Spreading new technology is not an end in itself. 
  Even the continued development of scientific knowledge in 
the 
area of climate could lead to continued political uncertainty 
for a long time. 
  An interesting development with potential consequences for 
technical development is the deregulation of certain energy 
markets which is under way. This "market-liberal" wave, which is 
an international phenomenon and includes, among other things, 
greater private ownership of energy companies, leads to a 
gradual transition from an express social service role in the 
direction of greater similarity with other industrial activity, 
including the same demands for financial profit for the owners 
and with a position that is tangibly more exposed to 
competition. Express social responsibility, for example in the 
form of delivery obligation and cost-based pricing, is beginning 
to dissolve. The role more similar to other industrial activity 
also includes introducing competition for customers. Previously, 
the energy companies had an assured customer base. Other 
companies were excluded through the concession. When the market 
is opened up, the producer does not sit as securely in his 
market, which introduces an additional element of risk into the 
commercial evaluation of new investment projects. 
  Against the background of the factors mentioned above, it 
appears likely that the companies' orientation to some extent 
will be guided toward activities that pay off more rapidly. This 
could have the consequence of reduced willingness to assume 
risks for long-range and uncertain technical development 
projects. 
  At the same time, experience in other areas indicates that 
competition stimulates technical development by increasing 
pressure on the organizations to use their resources in the most 
efficient manner. Experience from other technically similar 
industries, such as the chemical engineering industry or the 
forest industry, indicates that there is no conflict between 
short-term economic profitability and investments in long-term 
technical development and new technology; rather, the opposite. 
In a market exposed to competition, short-term profitability is 
a precondition for companies investing sufficiently much in 
R&amp;D 
and daring to undertake purchases of previously untested 
technology. Naturally, it is necessary to have the simultaneous 
capability and resources to do this. 
  Accordingly, the reduced risktaking indicated above is 
likely 
to be primarily a temporary phenomenon, which will mark the 
energy industry in the restructuring phase now under way. In the 
long run, competitive ability is created in this industry, just 
as in most other types of industrial activity, largely by 
investment in new technology. When the companies have found 
their new positions, the view of new technology will not be 
fundamentally different from what has traditionally been the 
case. 
  As was previously mentioned, we in Sweden used to have a low 
real interest rate for energy investments, that is to say the 
energy price increase was close to the nominal interest rates 
which favored major investments. Today, we have a deregulated 
credit market with high interest rates. There is much indication 
that the tendency of comparatively high interest rates and low 
inflation will continue for the future. This could affect the 
development in the direction of less investment-heavy technology 
and toward technology which involves shorter repayment periods. 
As a counterbalance to this tendency, there is now at the same 
time an internationalized credit market. This results in an 
equalization of the financial terms, and the internationalized 
capital market is likely in the long run to lead to more 
effective financial markets and thus to a certain downward 
pressure on interest rates. 
  One question for the future is whether today there is any 
relevance whatsoever in the technology triangle earlier 
described. As was mentioned in the previous section, the ties 
between the electrical engineering industry and the power 
industry have weakened, primarily as a result of the 
globalization of the supplying industry. The now ongoing 
deregulation of the electric power markets is likely to mean 
that the relationship between the power industry and the 
electricity-intensive industry will be affected. To a certain 
extent the power industry can be expected to focus a greater 
part of its interest on higher-paying customers in other 
countries. Society's role of stronger emphasis on market 
solutions, which is supported by the present EEA [European 
Economic Area]/EC adjustment, will further weaken the technology 
triangle, and for the future one might thus question whether it 
is not more or less in the process of dissolving. 
  With the greater internationalization in the wake of the 
EC's 
internal market, major changes are under way with general impact 
on society. The change in the financial markets and the 
transportation market will be especially great, of course. In 
the energy sector as well the consequences will be significant, 
although it is difficult to predict exactly what these changes 
will be. However, this increased internationalization further 
accentuates the need for acquiring knowledge and technology from 
the surrounding world. 
<H5>  4. Society and the Development of Energy Technology </H5>
  The following chapter discusses society's opportunities to 
influence commercial development of energy technology. The 
discussion is supplemented by the case study material which is 
given in Supplement 2. Society's impact on technical development 
can in principle be divided into two categories: 


    -  Efforts which influence the climate for technical 
development in society 
  -  efforts which are more directly aimed at stimulating all or 
certain innovation activity ("innovation support"). 

    The main purpose of this chapter is to discuss the latter 
activity. Since, during the course of the work, it has become 
increasingly clear that a favorable climate for technical 
development generally speaking is of much greater significance 
for the firms' development strength, we will begin by taking a 
closer look at climate factors of particular importance 
precisely for the development of energy technology. 
<H5>  4.1 The Climate for Technical Development </H5>
  The development which was described in the previous section, 
with more international competition and weaker national 
networks, further accentuates, if that is possible, the 
importance of the innovation climate for development. In order 
to be competitive, it is probably not enough for Sweden to have 
an innovation climate that is as good as in other countries. 
Sweden, with a small domestic market, large distances to 
customer markets, a minor language, etc., must, in order to 
compete, have a more favorable climate for industrial activity 
compared to those countries which have better preconditions 
because of size and geographic location. Five especially 
important climate factors for the development of energy 
technology have been identified: 


    -  Basic research and education 
  -  long-range stability in government regulations 
  -  the interest rate level 
  -  energy taxes and fees 
  -  general economic policy (inflation, tax burden) 

    Of these, the first and last ones are likely to be important 
in general, while the three in the middle are of special 
significance for the energy sector. This is due to the 
dependence on the long perspective in investments and the high 
capital intensity. 
  A great deal of know-how in basic research and education is 
essential, partly because of the research results as such, but 
perhaps to at least as large a degree as a source of good 
personnel for the companies. Competency in academic institutions 
is satisfactory in principle. However, there are areas in which 
society should try to strengthen the expertise. The fields most 
important to industry to which this applies is electric power 
technology and nuclear technology, fields which tend to be 
neglected in the government's major concentration on energy 
research. Previously, commerce and industry to some extent tried 
to compensate for this through its own efforts in academic 
institutions, which turned out not to be easy, in part because 
of the management forms of the institutions. 
  It is necessary for the political decisions of importance 
for 
the industry to be stable and have long-range credibility. In a 
situation where decisive factors affecting decisions cannot be 
predicted at all, the companies increase their concentration on 
the short-term perspective. Measures which offer extremely high 
flexibility will also be prioritized. Overall, these flexible 
solutions are not always the ones which would be most rational 
in a more stable environment. Long-range activities, 
particularly those which involve considerable commitments for 
the future, are shelved while waiting for the ability to have a 
better overview of the conditions. 
  As was mentioned in Chapter 2, the development of operating 
costs has often turned out to have a fundamental effect on 
profitability, because of the price development for energy raw 
materials and for the fiscal and fee policy. The market 
fluctuations in the raw material markets have been difficult to 
predict, particularly since 1973. By introducing yet another 
uncertainty in the form of variations in taxes and fees, the 
problems have become nearly insurmountable. During the 1980's 
the municipal energy companies, above all, operated in a very 
difficult environment in this respect, and the investments made 
in coal technology, for instance, during the first half of the 
1980's, supported by the government, turned out to be less 
successful after the state, within the course of a few years, 
raised the coal tax from zero to a level approximately three 
times higher than the coal price. 
  In one important respect, tax changes introduce an even 
greater assessment difficulty than normal market changes. Market 
changes are cyclical in nature. At the same time, investment 
decisions often have a lifetime spanning several market cycles. 
The result is that investment decisions contrary to the market 
development, if one succeeds in "overwintering" the downturn 
phase, often still turn out to be fortunate in the long term. 
Government regulations do not have this cyclical nature, which 
is why a decision that is "wrong," because future changes in 
government regulations were misjudged, rarely turn out to be 
fortunate. 
  The varying taxes on energy have not only increased market 
uncertainty, but have also had an immediate negative impact on 
the technical development by reducing the incentives for 
technical development. This effect can also be exemplified with 
the situation regarding the tax on coal. The proportion of tax 
of the total cost for coal mentioned above has varied greatly 
over a short time period. I today's situation coal can be 
converted to electric power using the most efficient and best 
environmentally adapted technology, with an efficiency of more 
than 40 percent. The hope for the new coal gasification 
technology is to be able to achieve an increase in efficiency of 
about 5-7 percent over a 10-20-year time frame. No matter how 
essential this improvement is, it is insignificant compared to 
the tax changes. Incentives to start a lengthy R&amp;D project to 
improve a process by some percentage point, while the rules may 
suddenly alter the cost by perhaps 10-20 percent, will be 
extremely limited. Instead, the businessman is likely to 
perceive that resources should be concentrated either to getting 
the decision pointed in a direction which favors his own 
interests, or not to do anything at all, while waiting and 
hoping for the situation to be clarified. 
  As was mentioned earlier, the interest level is of crucial 
importance for the profitability of the energy project, and thus 
for the opportunities for bringing about technical development. 
This applies especially to development of capital-intensive 
systems. The development under way in EEA/EC agreements has 
already resulted in an equalization of the interest level in 
various countries, a tendency which can be expected to continue. 
The interest level can thus not be influenced nationally as much 
as before, but in a small country such as Sweden it is primarily 
internationally determined and only slightly affected by the 
general economic climate. 
<H5>  4.2 Motives and Means of Innovation Support </H5>
[.sup]6[/] 
  Society's interest in the development of energy technology, 
just as in all other technical development, is, of course, to 
see to it that technical development progresses with good speed 
and that it gets an orientation which coincides with the general 
good. Doing so potentially involves three different types of 
influence: 


    -  Accelerating technical development 
  -  limiting the use of technology with consequences negative for 
society 
  -  guiding technical development toward the direction desirable 
for society. 

    In most areas of technology, society's interest has mainly 
involved the first aspect. In areas of technology where the 
activity has potentially negative consequences for people and 
environment, which concerns many types of processing industries 
including energy, society also has an interest in reducing or 
completely eliminating the use of certain types of technology. 
In the field of energy, the third type of influence has also 
been of significance, for example in the form of society's 
selectively having tried to stimulate certain technology such as 
wind power, bioenergy, etc. 
  It is not obvious that society needs to take any 
responsibility for technology development by businesses. In a 
functioning market, the technology needed will be produced and 
is economically defensible. The fundamental reason why society 
really has to stimulate technical development is therefore that 
there are said to be "market failures," which makes the motive 
for technical development by private organizations too weak from 
a socioeconomic aspect. Below, we list four arguments which have 
been brought up as to why this should be the case. 
  1. "R&amp;D results are of a collective nature, which is 
why the 
social benefits are greater than that of the individual company. 
Thus, projects exist which should be undertaken from a 
socioeconomic aspect, but which have no business-economic 
profitability and should therefore not be undertaken without 
subsidies." 
  2. "Companies and financiers avoid particularly risky 
activities if they can. It is usually said that they have a high 
aversion to risk. Since R&amp;D projects often carry unusually 
high 
risk, this results in few R&amp;D projects being started. This 
risk 
profile of technical development projects further causes the 
capital market to be unwilling to provide resources for this 
type of project. If it does, it is on particularly unfavorable 
terms." 
  3. "The costs of developing and, above all, investing in new 
technology of an infrastructure character are often of such 
extent that the capital market cannot cope with such large 
projects. If it does manage it, the terms will be particularly 
unfavorable, so the government must help." 
  4. "The assessment by the market of the usefulness and costs 
of technology can differ from that of society, for example by 
not fully including the environmental hazards from various types 
of technology in the companies' financial evaluation. Technology 
of major benefit to society must therefore be stimulated so that 
it becomes competitive." 
  These are thus fundamental reasons and, as is shown in 
sections 4.4 and 4.5, there is no lack of arguments against 
several of the reasons given above. 
  Means of Supporting Innovation 
  In principle there are three basic methods to formulate the 
means of controlling innovation: 


    -  Regulation 
  -  financial means of control 
  -  education and information 

    Regulation has traditionally been society's most important 
method for limiting negative environmental effects[.sup]7[/] 
in the energy sector. 
  The financial means of control can be of many kinds and 
include "carrots" (subsidies) and "whips" (fees) for 
development. Various categories of financial means of control 
are shown below. 
  Figure 4.1. Financial Means of Control in the Innovation 
Field 


    -  Subsidies (see below) 
  -  Taxes and fees 
  -  Government purchasing of technology 
  -  R&amp;D carried out or purchased by the state Source: 
According to 
Folster (1991) 

    Subsidies, in turn, can be provided in a number of different 
ways, according to the table below. 
  Figure 4.2. Innovation-Supporting Subsidies 


    -  General subsidies 
  -  R&amp;D tax deductions 
  -  General support for R&amp;D in specific industries 



      -  Selective Subsidies 
  -  Direct project grants 
  -  Subsidized loans 
  -  Loans with favorable terms 
  -  Loan guarantees 
  -  Honors Source: According to Folster (1991) 

    In order to accelerate the development, direct project 
grants 
to the energy field has been the principal method, while taxes 
and fees have obviously been the method for reducing the 
negative effects of technology application.[.sup]8[/] 
  Education and information are a third type of 
control.[.sup]9[/] By providing information about what is 
possible and how to go about it, a response is expected from the 
users. In general, information has not been used as much as a 
means of controlling innovation as the other two methods. That 
is because it is not known in advance to the same extent what 
the result of this type of measure will be. From this 
perspective, regulations are the most appealing, of course. 
<H3>  4.3 Experience of Swedish and Foreign Support for Energy 
Innovations </H3>
  In this section certain observations are made regarding the 
effects of supporting innovation. The material is based on both 
Swedish and foreign experiences, with a certain dominance for 
Swedish experiences. It is, of course, extremely difficult 
unambiguously to comment on the overall effects of a number of 
different measures. However, we outline a few principal 
directions regarding the experience. 
  The most successful role of Swedish society as a developer 
of 
new energy technology has been as owner of the former National 
Waterfall Agency, which, within the framework of the owner's 
political priorities, acted with integrity based on relevant 
technical and economic principles, and in this way greatly 
contributed to the development of energy technology in the 
country. Several of the most significant new products which 
originated in Sweden were developed for the needs of the 
Waterfall Agency. This has been a consequence of the 
enterprise's business activity and is therefore something 
different than government innovation support. It is thus not 
possible to draw any conclusions about the form of support which 
involves government technology purchasing based on the results 
achieved by the government's public service enterprises, a 
generalization which is sometimes done. 
  As for the innovation support, society's environmental 
regulations appear to be the most successful area. The measures 
have often led to the intended result. This is true in Sweden as 
well as abroad. In general, the support for innovation in order 
to guide the use of technology toward more environmentally 
friendly technology seems to be more or less without objection. 
However, in some cases application of these regulations has 
represented an obstacle to new technology. New technology always 
leads to certain breakin problems. The fact that in some cases 
temporary exemptions for emission regulations were not granted 
has caused the choice of more traditional solutions, which in 
the long run were probably poorer. 
  In several cases it is obvious that the financial support 
moved up the projects somewhat, which was not always good for 
the development process but led to the results having been 
forced out and immature products being presented to the market. 
  Among equipment manufacturers it is most striking how small 
the effect of the support has been for the companies' activity, 
and it is rarely that the support measures in themselves have 
initiated new projects. This relative disinterest should be 
viewed in the light of the R&amp;D function's strategic character 
for the long-term survival of the industrial enterprise. It is 
through the results for which the development function is 
responsible that survival is assured. The fact that the 
development costs are paid for is not enough of an incentive to 
put the company's best resources into development, but it 
requires a firm conviction that the projects will lead to 
products which in turn can generate a profit in a commercial 
market. 
  That does not always mean, however, that the companies are 
disinterested in support if such is available. Given that it has 
been decided to invest in a certain development, all 
opportunities for financing are welcome. This means that as long 
as economic support in various forms is given to companies, the 
companies will concentrate on obtaining these funds for projects 
which the company wants to undertake. The company will also, as 
long as it has a chance of getting the funds, stubbornly insist 
that the support is needed. 
  Among energy enterprises it has been more common that the 
opportunities for getting support have also affected the choice 
of which projects to carry out. This is probably because the 
development function is not the company's life blood in the same 
sense, and that covering the costs is therefore a stronger 
incentive. Another reason is that since support in various forms 
has been given for such a long time, the companies and their 
owners have in some cases "gotten used to" the fact that 
technical development is undertaken with partial government 
funding, and a lack of support means that the projects will not 
be undertaken. 
<H5>  4.4 The Principal Problems of Energy Innovation Support </H5>
  The following section deals with the problems which have 
emerged regarding financial innovation support, in particular, 
in which we also include subsidies such as taxation, aimed at 
prioritizing certain technology. These difficulties have 
primarily been of three kinds: social time frames, opportunities 
for successful project selection and the negative effects which 
can ensue from support. Experiences are based mainly on Swedish 
innovation support during the 1970's and 1980's. 
  The Project Selection 
  One reason for the problem with development support is that 
the government has had a difficult time making early, good 
assessments of development projects, which is why the very 
important project start rarely becomes very effective. The 
reasons for these problems are, in part, that it is complex to 
select the "right" projects to support, and partly that 
innovation programs must also take various political 
considerations, for example regional and energy-political ones, 
into account. 
  It is difficult to make a sensible choice of which 
technology 
to back. What is "a good project" signifies both that the 
project itself is promising and that it fits into the 
organization's overall strategy. It is thus difficult for an 
outsider to make these evaluations, even if he is professionally 
competent. 
  There are also reasons to assume that the selection will be 
"poorer" than would have been necessary, since an innovation 
support program is usually designed with regard for things other 
than finding "exactly the right" projects. Even if a political 
decision is right, there will soon be an election, which could 
mean that a new group with other priorities will come to power 
and that new projects will be given priority, before the old 
ones have "gotten there." Often, regional considerations are 
taken into account and other types of considerations, which in 
themselves could be justified, for example based on regional 
policy, but which could lead to certain other types of projects 
with less ability to compete being prioritized. 
  The Short Time Frames of Social Support 
  As was mentioned in Chapter 2, commercial technical 
development usually has a time frame of perhaps 10 years from 
idea to marketing. During this entire period the financial 
backers must, if needed, be prepared to come up with new 
resources in order to bring the project forward. Direct 
financial social support for the development of energy 
technology has been paid over an entirely different time scale, 
often encompassing no more than a three-year-period. A 
development project which stands and falls with the granting of 
a lot of support throughout the entire development period, is 
thus running a very large risk of failure. 
  The fact that funding is available for a normally limited 
period of time risks increasing the companies' shortsightedness 
and increase the market uncertainty. When support is given as a 
one-time contribution, for example in the form of an investment 
subsidy for a demonstration facility, it risks leading to an 
investment hump, followed by a drop when the support disappears. 
When the support is given in the form of running subsidies, the 
additional cost must be calculated over the relatively short 
period which the support can be assumed to span. During the 
1980's several companies made dubious investment decisions, in 
retrospect, as a result of not having anticipated that the 
regulations would change so quickly. Today, the enterprises have 
learned from this and in general practice greater caution in 
undertaking investments which depend on long-term contributions 
and subsidies for their profitability. 
  The awareness of the need for stable rules for industrial 
development has increased in society in recent years. To a 
certain extent this is a result of experiences in the field of 
energy technology in particular. The greater 
internationalization also has the result that more stability can 
be predicted for the future. At the same time, it must be 
concluded that there are hardly any chances of getting back to 
the stability which marked the development of the postwar 
period, because of an increasingly turbulent world. 
  Negative Effects of the Innovation Support 
  One motive for society's innovation support is also to 
influence the market-based incentives for development and 
application of technology. Of course, there are certain risks 
that the natural tendency toward innovation may be affected. In 
the energy field the following negative effects have been 
observed. 
  By "forcing" a development, for instance through a 
combination of development and introduction supports, one risks 
bringing a product to market which is actually not finished. 
This results in the early customers getting a negative view of 
the technology, which leads to a cool reception for mature 
products that have been further developed. 
  The most negative effect is of a psychological nature. The 
long-term subsidies have led to a not uncommon view among owners 
of energy companies that technical development should take place 
with society's support. This results in projects sometimes 
tending to be ranked according to wherever support is available, 
and that intrinsically promising projects are not followed up 
because no support can be obtained. 
<H3>  4.5 Is Continued Economic Support for Commercial Development 
of Technology Necessary? </H3>
  The motives for society to provide support for energy 
innovations have been of four different types, as was mentioned: 


    -  that R&amp;D is a collective product 
  -  that the companies have a high aversion to risk 
  -  that the capital market cannot cope with financing large 
projects, and 
  -  that negative environmental effects are not taken into 
consideration in the evaluation by the marketplace. 

    The Collective Nature of R&amp;D 
  On the average, R&amp;D projects undoubtedly provide a large 
amount of socioeconomic benefit. Within the energy sector, 
however, this is primarily due to a few projects which are very 
profitable both for the enterprise and for society. Few projects 
are not profitable from a business-economic point of view but 
should still be carried out from the aspect of society. In 
connection with the deregulation which is now under way in the 
energy markets, there is some risk that the great openness which 
has characterized the energy companies, with jointly owned 
development companies and projects, could decline somewhat. It 
is essential for the tradition of joint industrial projects and 
companies concerning research, education and evaluation of new 
technology to be able to continue, since these activities 
facilitate the spreading of knowledge within the industry, which 
ought possibly to be stimulated by a certain social support. 
  The Companies' Aversion to Risk 
  The companies within the energy sector have previously not 
generally avoided becoming involved in long-term development 
projects with technical and economic risks, if the potential 
gains from the development project were found to be sufficiently 
large. During the 1980's, tendencies toward a certain aversion 
to risk could be glimpsed. This is to some extent a result of 
the general economic development during the 1980's. But it is 
chiefly a result of the plentiful supply of government funding 
available for the "right" projects. Since the energy industry is 
marked by large, financially secure, companies, there are also 
no major financial difficulties in undertaking development 
projects. We thus looked only at the special need to support 
companies for energy technology development. To the extent 
general commercial subsidies are available, for instance in 
order to facilitate obtaining risk capital by small and 
medium-sized companies, energy companies should of course have 
the same opportunities as others. 
  The Capacity of the Capital Market 
  With the internationalized capital market, the financing of 
new energy technology infrastructures at reasonable cost is 
managed without direct government help. A reason for the 
government to support this can only occur as a result of rapid 
abolition of nuclear power. This could conceivably lead to a new 
wave of investments, which would have enormous consequences for 
the electric power market, unless a part of the financing is 
passed onto society. 
  External Market Factors 
  Reducing environmental effects by means of internalizing 
environmental costs will continue to be an important field for 
society, preferably in international cooperation. It should be 
noted in this connection that in the majority of cases 
regulations are the method which has been used for successful 
contributions, despite the fact that fees are regarded as 
preferable from a strictly economic aspect. This is because it 
is much easier to "know what you get" with a regulation, and 
that a regulation can be a clearer signal to the market about 
what is needed. Environmental fees have often turned out to be a 
blunt instrument. A contributing cause for this is that it can 
be easy to confuse fees as a means of stimulating technology 
development with the fiscal nature of fees. In principle, IVA is 
not opposed to economic means of control if handled correctly, 
that is to say as a means of control and not as a means of 
taxation, and if the field is suitable for this type of control. 
<H3>  5. Recommendations Regarding Society's Role in Commercial 
Development of Energy Technology </H3>
  In Chapter 2 the success factors for technical development 
projects were analyzed and the extent to which the energy field 
differs in this respect from other fields of technology. Chapter 
3 dealt with development patterns for technical development in 
the energy sector, and Chapter 4 analyzed society's means of 
influencing the companies' technical development, as well as 
Swedish and foreign experiences of the measures employed. 
  Society's most important task, in order to facilitate the 
development of energy technology, is to create an industrial and 
innovation climate which leads to good profitability development 
in the businesses and thus to investments in industrial activity 
being more profitable than investments in property, for example. 
  One condition for a well-functioning business community is a 
functioning research system, which is capable of supplying 
business and industry with new knowledge and new carriers of 
knowledge. This requires high-quality research at universities 
and academic institutions in fields of technology relevant to 
business and industry. In order to assure this relevance, 
expanded cooperation between business and academic institution 
is needed. This concerns above all the opportunities for 
universities and academic institutions to obtain stimuli and 
signals from business and industry regarding essential research 
fields. Within the framework for this, there should be much 
greater academic freedom regarding the research field. 
  A the same time society should bear primary responsibility 
for financing basic research and education. In today's situation 
society takes too little responsibility for this in some areas 
which are of major importance for the energy sector. In some 
cases the result was that industry had to come in and help 
finance such activity, for example regarding the Electric Power 
Center at the Royal Institute of Technology (KTH). In other 
cases, altogether too little activity is being carried out, for 
example in reactor technology. Simultaneously, the energy 
industry is facing major changes from having been a national 
industry with service character to greatly increased 
internationalization. Because we are a small country, it is 
particularly important that we are capable of participating in 
the international cooperation and exchange of experience. It is 
therefore essential for academic research to be given greater 
ability to exchange experiences and time for adjustment to the 
R&amp;D programs which exist within the EC, above all. 
  Society should therefore increase its funding of direct 
academic research within consumer-specific fields, help expand 
the contact surfaces between academic institutions and the 
business community, and create more resources for participating 
in international programs. One should also strive for more 
international exchanges and active participation in planning and 
undertaking international research cooperations, in order to 
increase international influence on Swedish energy research. 
  The energy sector has been characterized by major 
uncertainty 
during the 1970's and 1980's. This is in part a result of market 
fluctuations, in part a result of major turbulence regarding the 
fiscal and fee policy as well as regarding the future of nuclear 
power. Energy taxes are of fundamental importance for the 
profitability of investments. In the future, regulatory and fee 
systems must be designed in a more consistent, more credible and 
more durable way, so that preconditions are created for a stable 
market and, consequently, opportunities for the companies to 
develop and invest in new, more efficient and, for the 
environment, more acceptable products and systems. 
  Within the energy sector society not only has an interest in 
technical development proceeding rapidly, but also in the 
application of technology being shifted over toward technology 
which has minor, or preferably no, impact on the environment. In 
remarkably many instances the market forces have been able to 
produce this greater environmental adaptation. One example is 
the development of technology for bleaching cellulose. Society 
has a self-evident responsibility to monitor that this is the 
case, and, where that does not happen, society's largely 
successful work in the environmental sector must go on. 
  However, measures in this area must to an increasing degree 
be announced in advance or at least be foreseeable with a 
certain priority, since the measures could otherwise lead to 
reduced willingness to take risks. There must also be a certain 
flexibility in the regulations, so that during the introductory 
period there is some margin in the event the new technology 
cannot cope with the imposed standards. If not, the rules risk 
having a technology-preserving effect. To the extent economic 
means of control are used, they must be used as a means of 
improving the environment, for example, and not as a way to 
augment government revenue. Furthermore, economic means of 
control must not be used in combination with regulation, since 
they will then automatically get this fiscal character and not 
be technology-promoting. Measures should naturally be undertaken 
in such a manner and at such a pace that the opportunities for 
carrying out industrial activity in Sweden is not adversely 
affected. Measures should be undertaken in international 
cooperation or at least in coordination with the international 
development. 
  Other than means of control intended to internalize 
environmental costs, we believe that if the innovation climate 
for energy technology can be reinforced with the measures 
mentioned above there is no need for direct financial support 
for the development of energy technology directed toward 
individual companies or smaller groups of companies. New 
technology will mainly enter the energy system in connection 
with new investments. During the 1990's the need for new 
investments in the Swedish energy system appears to be of 
limited extent. The opportunities for broad distribution of new 
technology in Sweden in the short term is extremely limited, and 
contributions aimed at a rapid breakthrough of new supply 
technology will scarcely be successful. 
  Subsidies are also not the solution for supporting the 
technical development in the developmentally "weak" industries. 
A considerable portion of the subsidies have, particularly as 
regards multifamily dwellings and premises, been a poorly 
functioning market. Deregulation and increased competition can 
be expected to result in these markets functioning better in the 
future. This is indicated by the positive development involving 
energy management in small houses, a market which has worked 
much better as a result of tough competition and less extensive 
subsidies. 
  The situation among municipal energy plants is more 
difficult. The industry is developmentally weak, primarily as a 
result of its weak owners, who did not permit the companies to 
allocate resources for new technical development projects. The 
tendency has been reinforced by the ample support which has been 
given to this sector, since it permitted the strategy mentioned 
above. It is possible to speak of the development support having 
functioned as some sort of "drug" for the companies. If the 
support were not available it would be more obvious to owners 
that they have to make decisions to invest in technical 
development, and the incentives for development would thus be 
increased. 
  This negative view of the effectiveness of financial support 
also includes government purchasing of technology. To be sure, 
there are examples that the ongoing technology purchasing 
program has contributed to several successful development 
projects. IVA's assessment is, however, that these development 
processes would have come about anyway. Therefore, the program 
has instead been successful in catching on early to a 
development already established by the market, rather than 
establishing new development processes. It is also remarkable 
that in the area of making energy more efficient there have been 
several parallel activities initiated by various players, both 
government and private, something which may be questioned. 
  In sum, the conclusion of this reasoning is that direct 
government efforts directed toward supporting the companies' 
development of new energy technology will not be of decisive 
importance for the development of future energy 
technology.[.sup]10[/]. This applies to both support for new 
supply technology and new application technology. The more 
extensive subsidies for this orientation given at present are 
the Energy Technology Fund, the Experimental Construction 
Support and the Technology Purchasing Support for more efficient 
energy technology. We propose a cancellation of these subsidies. 
The Energy Technology Fund and the Technology Purchasing Program 
each have a budget of about 150-200 million kronor a year up to 
1996, and the Experimental Construction Program about 10 million 
a year. 
  In connection with the increased market orientation and 
internationalization which the energy industry is undergoing, it 
is particularly important to retain the valuable Swedish 
tradition of extensive cooperation within the energy industry. 
Joint research by a specific industry is an important method for 
this. It is reasonable that some of the funds released above 
should be shifted to stimulating these jointly owned development 
projects and development companies. It is essential for this 
activity to be managed under its own responsibility. With a view 
to the greater internationalization and the need for greater 
international influences within the sector, it would be 
especially desirable if society could also contribute to joint 
industrial research in which international players are 
participating and thus be able to share the results. 
Strengthening joint research in an industry need not mean 
establishing new institutes, which risk becoming rigid and in 
the long term less flexible, a problem often indicated for 
certain joint industrial research. The activity should therefore 
mainly be conducted by the member companies. 
