<H5>  Endnotes </H5>
  1. Just as interesting as studying successful commercial 
projects is to study failed commercial projects. Here concepts 
such as stop factors (or failure factors) are used. There are 
few documented failed projects, however, primarily because 
technology developers or their companies do not want to 
advertise failed projects officially. A study which makes paired 
comparisons between successful and unsuccessful projects is the 
SAPPHO study (Freeman, 1982). 
  2. The direct development cooperation between a technology 
developer and a government buyer in the form of a state-owned 
corporation or such has been very successful historically. As 
examples of such cooperations outside the energy field may be 
mentioned ABB-SJ (trains), Ericsson-Telecommunications Agency 
(telephones), Saab-FMV (aircraft) and Bofors--FMV (weapons). 
  3. This did not mean that they acted as "technical patrons" 
for the industry, which has sometimes been inaccurately 
indicated. The development has been to the advantage of both 
parties. 
  4. Something which, however, was mostly a result of the 
vague 
manner of Swedish energy statistics in comparing electrical and 
thermal energy. 
  5. This trend is thus not limited to energy technology. 
  6. By innovation support in this text we mean all types of 
measures to support the development and use of certain new 
technology. This can also take place for example through 
information campaigns, etc. Support should thus not be 
interpreted as just financial subsidies. 
  7. In Supplement 2 three cases of such public influence are 
described: the German power industry's adjustment to 
SO[.sup]x[/]/NO[.sub]x[/] rules, Swedish nuclear waste 
technology and the adjustment of the pulp and paper industry to 
regulations for emission of organochlorine compounds. 
  8. In our collection of examples there are three cases of 
the 
latter type of means of control: the Swedish development in the 
bioenergy field and the heat pump field, and activities for 
efficient use of electric power in the United States. 
  9. Experiences are given in the collection of examples of 
the 
effort with energy advisers which was undertaken in the early 
1980's. 
  10. This should not be interpreted as criticism of the way 
these activities were conducted by responsible officials. On the 
contrary; these activities were carried out in a professional 
manner. 
  11. In 1979 Defibrator was absorbed into Sunds and Sunds 
changed the name to Sunds Defibrator. 
  12. It should be mentioned that the groundwood process as 
well has developed gradually. By also putting this process under 
pressure, so-called pressure grinding, lignins are plasticized, 
from which a stronger pulp is obtained than in the original 
atmospheric process. The process, developed by Tampella, gives a 
pulp which is used for higher qualities, such as journal paper. 
  13. Stal Laval was a wholly owned subsidiary of ASEA. In 
1984 
it changed its name to ASEA STAL. The development of PFBC was 
done at Stal Laval up to 1983 and after that at the ASEA PFBC 
company, which changed its name to ABB Carbon in 1988. PFBC is 
today carried out at ABB Carbon, which now is a wholly owned 
subsidiary of ABB. 
  14. In 1985 Ericsson's activity was reorganized and Ericsson 
Cables was formed, of which Sieverts Kabelverk was a part. 
Sieverts Kabelverk had long been a wholly owned subsidiary of LM 
Ericsson. 
  15. Each cable usually includes 12 fibers, but up to 36 
fibers can be found today. 
  16. By Germany in this case description is meant the Federal 
Republic, since the description generally deals with the period 
before unification with the GDR. 
  17. More than 80 percent of the nation's power supply is the 
so-called public electricity supply (Oeffentliche 
Elektrizitaetsversorgung). This group includes all enterprises 
which according to the Law on Promotion of the Power Industry 
(Gesetz zur Foerderung der Energiewirtschaft) are obligated to 
deliver power to a third party. Today there are about 1,000 such 
enterprises. The capital funding for the public power industry 
is mainly public (municipal, land or federal). 
  18. The emission limits are based on half-hourly levels, in 
which the limits may never exceed more than 100 percent. In 
Sweden the emission quantities are compared to the amount of 
added fuel. Further, the Swedish limits are average annual 
values. A fair comparison between Swedish and German measurement 
requirements can therefore not be made. Also, power plants with 
an added thermal output of 300 MW are given sealed equipment for 
continuous measurement of emissions. The measurement data are 
monitored and stored by independent monitoring organizations. 
  19. By biofuels are here meant forest fuels, including 
forest 
waste, and cultivated energy forest. Hay and reeds are also 
included, but the addition of these fuels is so limited that 
they are not discussed here. The forest industry's utilization 
of lyes, barks, sawdust, etc. in energy production will also not 
be discussed here, since this deals mainly with conversion from 
oil undertaken without any major government measures. It should 
be noted that the area "bioenergy" also included peat at the 
beginning of the period. When the field of "peat" received its 
own funding in the energy programs, the concept of "biofuels" 
began to apply more to forest fuels. The peat support has been 
about 400 million kronor during the period from 1975 to 1990, a 
large part of which was intended for investment support for 
facilities. Today, however, biofuels and forest fuels are 
equated. 
  20. Of these funds 40 million kronor were for 
production-related projects and 35 million kronor for combustion 
technology, both for forest fuels and peat. 
  21. Heat pumps are not intrinsically new. The first 
medium-sized heat pump was installed as early as 1858 in 
Salzkammergut in Austria in order to reduce the costs of the 
heat needed for salt production. The concept is in principle the 
same as is still used. 
  22. In addition to these funds, a certain amount of 
additional support was given to installation of heat pumps in 
multifamily dwellings, the so-called ROT program. 
  23. The volume of these indirect subsidies is difficult to 
estimate. 
  24. After 1989 a considerable number (10,000 units in 1990) 
of cheap, so-called comfort heat pumps, were sold to homes with 
direct-working electric radiators. Since it provides a very 
small energy saving, but is primarily being bought for reasons 
of comfort, it is doubtful to compare it with the other types of 
heat pumps. The relevance of the figure for 1990 may therefore 
be questioned. 
  25. The development has instead approximately followed the 
development of the price relationship between oil and 
electricity. 
  26. ASEA entered the market by way of an accentuated need 
for 
diversification at the end of the 1970's. The market for 
turbines was eliminated with the collapse of the shipyard 
industry and the limitation of the nuclear power program to 12 
reactors. 
  27. The interest should be viewed in connection with the 
fact 
